SUMMARY
The project has a strong architectural foundation in documentation and backend scaffolding, but it is currently in a state where nothing actually runs end-to-end. The database has no init script, the Android app has no build system, and there are zero tests. The most impactful next action is a two-track parallel effort: (1) fix the database so the backend services can actually start and serve data, and (2) build the Android Gradle skeleton so the Kotlin files can compile into an APK. Once those two blockers are cleared, the path to a working MVP is implementing the Report flow (Room + Ktor + Compose UI + WorkManager sync) -- which is the "one killer feature" that proves the core value proposition to real users in a real Nairobi ward.

The project is at the end of "Sprint Zero" (infrastructure scaffolded but not yet functional). The next phase is Phase 1: The "One Killer Feature" MVP -- incident reporting with public tracking, targeting 20-50 users in a single Nairobi ward within 6-8 weeks.

